He loves to talk about how smart he is and namedrop.  He's basically that guy at the party that loves himself and thinks everyone else wants to hear him talk about how smart he is.  For someone who teaches a communications course, he is surprisingly insufferable.

Prof. Labash's industry expertise is indispensable.  Taking any of his courses will make you a better communicator, a better listener and, as such, a better leader.  I highly recommend any course with Prof. Labash.
He is not clear
Great teacher, made class interesting and was very knowledgeable.
Very bad experience. He made easy things complicated. Grading   was awful with no explanations given later.
Chris's class was my favorite class this past semester.
Very helpful teacher! Very kind and professional!
Good teacher. Very nice and willing to help.
She is a really great teacher, and super nice. She was always willing to help and clarify things.
Unclear, unhelpful and uninspiring. I dreaded this class with her the most out of all the classes I took in college.
very helpful and willing to listen, but does not have a very clear grading scheme and gives vague feedback
She's so sweet and makes the class a true joy.
She obviously has a lot of knowledge, but that means nothing if she cannot illustrate her point or give clear instructions. A very frustrating teacher to have. Never understand what she wants.

Took the racism freshman seminar where the class was 'co-taught' by him, Richard Purcell, and Mariana Achugar. He has a very loud and dynamic personality, which I found a bit cringe as he'd take over (read: interrupt) the conversation from the two and talk for looong amounts of time. Class was pretty easy, most people didn't really participate.

Prof Slate is AMAZING! His classroom is a really friendly, respectful environment that is perfect for in depth discussions or debates. The class wasn't very difficult, but it definitely made me think, and I would recommend it for anyone to take. It is obvious when Prof Slate teaches that he loves what he does, and its infectious!

This is not a history class. It makes too many untested sociological/ political assumptions. I feel like it teaches you what you should think in this western mainstream political and historical rhetoric, so I am actually quite annoyed by that. However I would say the professor is nice.

Professor Slate is the best. He's the nicest guy ever, and he really makes an effort to get to know his students. His lectures are really interesting. Definitely take as many courses with him as you can.
Easygoing guy, very enthusiastic about his subject. His class can make you feel like you're in grade school again (he calls everyone "friends" and emphasizes partnering up) but overall a good prof.
Awesome teacher, he knows his stuff.
Awesome, awesome guy with an infectious passion for what he teaches. Even if you've disliked history before, he'll make you like it.
This prof is so good that at the end of every lecture, you just want to stand up and in your best Mortal Kombat voice yell "Slate Wins!......Flawless Victory."
Great professor who was clearly very passionate about his work. Very understanding and engaging.

The class was Civil Rights and World History. Professor Slate is a great guy and teacher. He is extremely helpful and his TA Kaaz is really helpful too. I recommend taking his class. As long as you put in effort,  you will pass with a good grade.
Amazing professor, very interested in the topic. Makes an effort to get to know his students, so take advantage of his office hours! Attendance is not taken, but you'll miss A LOT if you skip.
Hands down the best professor I've ever had, has become a role model of mine. Passionate and inspiring; he truly loves history and his students.

Very good intro to calculus course. Should be super simple if you've had any calc background. Even if you haven't, prof Brandon is wonderful and begs the students to ask questions. She makes herself available if you need any help and is very thoughtful. If you get an A on all three exams you don't have to take the final, which is super nice.
Deb's class is amazing! I learned so much, and she is very understanding and helpful with all her students.  Take her if you can. Will not disappoint
Deb is the BEST professor i've had in college. She is ALWAYS willing to help and pushes you beyond what you think your ability is. She is also a fun and loving character!

I graduated a couple years ago, and it was thanks to professor brandon. I was a humanities major who HAD to take a calc class (as you can infer math is not my strongest subject) and she took the time to help me conquer calc. Many thanks to professor brandon for being so understanding and helpful.
Best professor I've ever had. Sometimes I would even go to her office hours just to talk, extremely cool person and really understanding of students.

One of my favorite professors. Goes to great lengths to make sure our enormous lecture does not have any questions about topics before moving on. She is always willing to answer questions a million ways until you understand. Brandon keeps Calculus light and occasionally fun--a great accomplishment. Go to lecture/recitation, ask questions, get an A.
I had her for Diff EQ in 2000 and at that time she didnt seem very interested in the class or the students very much at all.

Best calc teacher I ever had.  Encyclopedic coverage of topics, but always willing to walk you through stuff.  Expects you to learn, and works to support that.  It's an easy class if you work hard, and a hard class if you treat it like it's easy.
She was a pretty good teacher.  A LOT of quizzes, too many in fact... exams were decent... very understandable and good at explaining things.

One of the best calc professors I've had. Excellent at lecturing, and would always be able to clear up any confusion you had on concepts. Had very realistic expectations of students, and was fun and energetic in class. Exams were fairly easy.
Very very hard, and goes blazingly fast during lecture...like 20 boards within an hour!
challenging class, but she is VERY good.
I got striaght 76%'s by no fault of hers. But I've heard that Matrix can be taught MUCH better.
she's the reason I just graduated with a math degree.  wonderful person.

Excellent professor. The course can be very hard, but the way she teaches it makes it much easier. Her notes are VERY helpful. This is definitely one of those few courses where you don't want to skip the lectures. Review sessions for exams are HELPFUL!
This teacher is mean, and nasty.  I didn't like her, and she sucked.

Like him a lot, would recommend to anyone.

DeBoer is possibly the nicest professor in the world. His lectures are easy to follow. He prints out notes leaving certain words blank (to be filled in throughout the lecture)= good study guide and resource for homework. Homeworks take long, unexpectedly difficult Exam 3.

First semester professor at time of this writing.  Will ramble/mumble and completely ignore questions during lecture, often responding improperly ("what are p, c, and n?", "p is a variable, c is a constant, and n is an exponent").  Unfortunately, he's the only one who teaches MechE Thermo.  Easier to learn from book than from lectures.
So nice and understands that the language is difficult. Definitely going to take a class with him again.
I really enjoyed his class.  He loves teaching and he treats his students well.  Going to miss his class!
He would like it if everyone could learn Chinese and got an A. If you let him he will help you.
Liu is amazing as a teacher. he is patient and will take the time to help you learn the language. I love this class and hope to have him again next semester

Very knowledgeable regarding international relations (she was the former Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs, after all - she has a wiki page). Explains things well. Attendance for Diplomacy and Statecraft is not mandatory as far as I can tell. There are quite a few readings for the class. It's worth taking as an Int'l Relations major.

She is very very kind. She gives very interesting lectures, and really pays attention to class feedback. I am really enjoying her class and highly recommend. the discussions make me feel very close to my other classmates, and the learning environment is wonderful.
Her lectures and the readings are very engaging. You will learn a lot by showing up to class.

Great teacher; very enthusiastic about and interested in linguistics. She was the advisor for the major, but it changes every so often. She's clear in her explanations. Nature of Language with her is relatively simple if you get the concepts, and homework is once every 2-3 weeks. Not many exams. As a Linguistics major, I like her.
It was a good class and not that hard if you paid attention and used your brain

Prof. Bernhard has a thick accent which makes it sometimes hard to understand; however, many find his humor to be dry (yet, I found it hilarious). While I was unable to keep Inorganic in my schedule for the full year, I enjoyed having Bernhard as prof. He gives open note/open book exams and final, so he really wants the students to do well.

Bernhard was an alright professor.  Notes seem to lack a bit of structure and organization.  He's got a dry sense of humor that's easy to miss if you're not paying attention.  Office hours at terrible time, but helpful if you actually go.

He is very smart, but does not know how to teach well. Attending lecture doesn't help; he just states facts seemingly at random, and does not provide notes. The textbook is really my teacher. The grading scheme is strange/unpredictable, but he does seem to give a large curve.

Really enjoyed the course. The key is to engage (true of all IR), which I suspect the other student didn't do much of. If you attend with your opinions or any thoughts on current events and IR theories, you'll glean significant value from the professor's insights and experiences. Absolutely helped my acuity in understanding politics. Fun, as well.

He's a terrible lecturer. I was really excited to learn about conflict resolution, but the class was completely useless. He will have you read things that require tons of background information that he does not provide. There were 6 or 7 case studies listed in the course description, and we spent two weeks on all of them put together. Useless.

Questionable lecturer, but great at answering questions. She kinda just proves things on the board the whole hour. Half the class skips lecture, and it seems the people who skip and read the book do better in the class than those that go to lecture. Also, her exams are not that hard. They are tricky, but not difficult. The TA teaches everything.

Again, it's Japanese, and it's Intermediate Japanese I at that, so it's getting a bit hard. Native speaker (and it's the second year), so he talks mostly in Japanese, stopping to translate into English when we don't get it. Harder work, more work, etc. Get used to it.
Kinda boring but he knows his stuff. Very nice and answers questions well. Overall recommend. Tests are straight forward, no surprises.
Dr. Yaron can be a little dull in his lectures, but he is always more than willing to answer any question during lecture.

He is a professor that knows his topics extremely thoroughly. Explains most of the concepts pretty clearly. Homework and tests are veeeery reflective of the problems we do in class. Tests are EASY. He gives random chemistry facts related to real life situation which makes it really interesting. Seems to not like the New England Patriots.

Yaron's lectures are a little dry but he gets the point across pretty well. He gives notes sheets with basic info on them so the class is very organized. There is a lot of homework in this class, but it relates well to the concepts. There are 3 midterms worth 100 points each, and one of them can be completely dropped or you can drop half the final.

Honestly, I never went to lecture and I'm sitting pretty with a high B. Yaron is extremely dry and not engaging, but don't expect the class to be a breeze if you don't put in the work. A good chemistry background and a good TA is necessary to understand the concepts taught because Yaron often has difficulty explaining basic concepts.

Professor Yaron is pretty clear cut. He explains the concepts well, and lets you know what he is looking for on the homework or on an exam. I think he is very clear and willing to help you if you ask for it. Great class! 10/10 would take again.. I hope I ace this class.

Sometimes he doesn't do the best job of explaining a new concept and has trouble rearticulating it when someone asks for clarification.  The homework assignments often have seemingly nothing to do with the textbook or lectures, and you have to specifically ask the TAs to learn how to do them.  Not an awful teacher, but not always the clearest.

Professor Yaron needs to be more confident! He understands the subject matter and why it matters well, but is too sheepish teaching it.   Also, doesn't do a great job integrating math into the content.
Lectures can be a bit dry, but it's a fairly straightforward class content-wise.
Great professor! Definitely my favorite that semester.

Lots of reading (a reading journal entry or an argument outline sketch due every class) but very detailed, lots of interesting debatesdiscussion, and pretty thought-provoking. Pay attention in class! Work hard and do the readings and it will be rewarding.
Lectures are discussion format, so don't take the class if you're not ready to contribute at least a little. Great coverage of very interesting topics, and not a ton of work overall.

He knows his material, and is willing to teach it. His lectures often take discussion formats and he facilitates student discussion with him guiding it; if this appeal to you, the class itself will be enjoyable. However, grading is done by TA, while he is willing and accommodating to help students, the result is that he has little impact on grades.
Obvious that he has a passion for teaching and philosophy. Really wants students to learn and understand concepts. But too much work... TAs do pretty much all of the grading.

Terrible professor. Does not handle any aspect of grades nor does he care about any aspect of grades and delegates everything to TAs. Lectures are mildly interesting, but assigns an absurd amount of work.

Awesome class, as long as you put in the effort. Participate in discussions, and read all of the assignments closely and you will get a lot out of this class. I was not his biggest fan in the beginning, but looking back his class was one of the best experiences of freshman year. Nice guy too.

He's a pretty good professor in general. Knows his stuff and is somewhat interesting. He's not very helpful and directs you to the TAs and grading always depends on the TA. Depending on the TA you'll either get an easy A or you'll get a C.

I had him for my freshman seminar, Voting Theory (I still have no idea how I ended up in it). Attendance is not required, and there is literally no work at all besides the final paper. (Even then, I could have passed without handing it in, apparently. Weird.) He's very relaxed and friendly. I enjoyed the class.

Apparently a doctoral student. I took both Elementary Japanese I and II with him. The difficulty of the class mostly has to do with the level of work (there's homework every day there's class - 4 days a week). He is enthusiastic and tries to be helpful. (He's also a native speaker, which is good for learning, but can make understanding difficult).
He laughs a lot at his own jokes.
The class is sorta boring and you really need to pay attention to grasp whats going on. Tests are almost identical to practice but the final was pretty tough.

Lectures are entertaining, but you don't learn much. He's a nice, funny guy, and he's enthusiastic about the material he teaches, but you learn most of the material from reading the textbook and trying to do the homework. Exams are exactly like the practice exams.
Amazing teacher. Would 100% recommend him as a teacher and this class. Very into what he teaches which make the class fun.

Absolutely hated this class.  He is horribly inefficient and unorganized and he babbles to himself in lecture.  He has you complete these little quizzes in lecture to check attendance, but he barely covers half of the stuff on the page.  His antics in lecture aren't funny either; it is just plain annoying.
babbles to himself, lectures worse than useless
The class is hard and boring. He murmurs to himself and you cant hear what he's saying.

Very entertaining! Uses a fire extinguisher in class to demonstrate flux, totally awesome.  He's friendly, cool accent and tests are challenging but fair.  He also TA's for other classes, so is able to teach on a personal level too (in office hours).
This guy is funny! Go in to his office hours, he's very nice on the personal level, and is willing to do as much as he can to help
Hilarious. Kept class interesting. Tests weren't easy, but they weren't hard either. They were fair. If you study, do the homework, and go to class, you'll do fine.
horrible teacher, didn't help at all and wasn't able to understand him half the time. would never take a class by him again

I found her lectures to be very refreshing. She doesn't like to plug and chug, she's more into taking it slow and just writing out a complete set of notes. There is a very even rhythm to her sliding the chalk against the blackboard, and she is almost computer-like... but in a good way. recommend taking 210 with maggie

Class is pretty laid back. If you go and pay attention its an easy A. Problem is no one goes. Friday rec. is completely worthless. Do good on all the HW and decent on the tests for an A-B. She writes all X's as N's which gets annoying, but she is a good teacher and easy to understand if you pay attention. Posts slides from class online

I took 33-106 with him over the summer. Great man that really cares about his students, if you ever need help he'll find a way to help you. The class was a lot of work but nothing impossible, he teaches the material well. If you care you're going to learn because he cares to teach the stuff.

He is one of the best teachers I've had. Incredibly enthusiastic and makes an effort to meet all students on a personal level and help them excel. Always available for help with physics or just plain advice. Just try to answer a question every now and then, and he'll love you. P.S. I took him summer class, which was smaller. Take it!

He was the worst professor I have ever had. If you can, do not take his class. He was not clear whenever he lectured and kept getting on tangents. The tests? Literally nothing you have ever seen before on homeworks or quizzes.  It was an "introduction class" that barely introduced physics to you. Just a bunch of derivations not even needed.
Energetic, sometimes hard to understand, very passionate. If I was majoring in physics (and didn't suck at it), I'd love to have him as an advisor.

Incredibly energetic and uses hilarious examples to illustrate physical points. Sometimes difficult to follow in lecture, but a great guy who is genuinely happy to teach. Material is hard, but worthwhile.
Very interesting professor. I'm not sure if he can actually teach since so many people failed or dropped out of the class but the lectures are interesting.

Dr. Ghosh is the only man I know who runs across the room with a meter stick when talking about vectors. It is just about impossible to fall asleep in his class, which says a lot about a physics professor. He is the undergrad physics advisor and one of CMU's best assets. Not many people care about students as much as he does. He is there to help.

He is so awesome. You couldn't fall asleep in his class if you tried. He is very friendly in person. He is an advisor to many, so he is busy. When he is not busy he is great to talk to. I wish he would teach all my classes.

Class is "easy", but he expects CRAZYINESS from you. Hes a nice and funny guy, and teaches you things in class, but they probably won't have anything to do with the class. Nice guy, difficult to explain things to.

He's definetly the most energetic professor I've ever had. Passionate about physics, and will get you passionate too (even if you hate the subject and are just taking the class for the lab credit). Good at explaining experiments and their background information, and has realistic expectations. Highly recommended.
I like his method of teaching (compared to the first professor). Also has a sense of humor and we laugh a lot in his class. The exams were a bit harder than the one the first professor gave.
Don't expect to learn anything in lectures.
The only class where you can take the derivative of an elephant

column1: I wanted to fail just to have him as a prof again

rComments: excellent prof, learned a lot

Overall she is a pretty good teacher. She guides the discussions pretty well and she picks a lot of different, interesting readings. She is really helpful (especially if you ask). I would recommend taking her class.

Enthusiastic and fun. Class was almost all discussion-based on very interesting topics. Prof. Lundgren let us go pretty much where we wanted with our discussions, but I still feel like I learned a lot about the topic. Essays were graded fairly lightly.

She's OK. The only trouble I have with her is that she can seem a bit whimsical every now and then. Her class is not difficult and she structures the material based on a rubric she hands out at the beginning of the semester.
Stacie is really sweet, but she and her partner, Steve Stadelmeier, create quite a dichotomy.

Rebecca Nugent has a lovely personality and makes the statistics class rather enjoyable. Some of the material is challenging, though she strives to give as much information as possible during the lectures, At some points, the pace is a bit quick and the homework can be difficult, but with the right level of effort, the class is easy to handle.
Hot professor  lectures are extremely fast paced, she'd go over a ton of materials but doesn't post lecture notes so if you don't pay attention to her lecture you'd be lost and suffer in statistics
Great prof, but extremely fast pace. (Covered 4 months worth of material in 7 weeks) Homeworks are quite hard.
Dr. Nugent is the best professor I have ever had in CMU. She is smart and knows what she is teaching really well. She will always make you laugh :)

Like a lot of professors, she's fairly nice and quite helpful.  However, she has exceptional teaching prowess, and is hilarious.  And she's super smart on statistical concepts, namely networks and the concepts of basic graph theory that she teaches in her Freshman Seminar in statistics.  Them guest lectures are usually pretty reliable as well.
She's awesome, so is Statistics:)
She's the coolest professor ever!

She was by far the worst professor I had at CMU. She was late to class more often than not, shamed her students for not understanding her teaching, was generally defensive/mean/narcissistic. I don't think it's appropriate for her to be teaching. To be fair, it's been several years since I was in her class. Perhaps she has improved.
Not willing to listen, sometimes ignore students questions or their explanations for asking questions. Sometimes late to class, sometimes canceled class for no reason.

I found her to be extremely approachable and easy to go to for help. She cares very much about the progress of her students and is willing to spend as much time as necessary outside of class to help them. I found the switch to powerpoint to be particularly helpful in grasping the content and bigger picture ideas. I would definitely recommend her!

Terrible teaching ability. Very stubborn & refuses to admit when she's wrong. Used incorrect equations in class.  Doesn't listen to students & overall quite unprofessional. Was late to most classes & 15 minutes late on an exam day & then ran out of exams. Def would not recommend taking this class with her at all. Take a harder class w/ better prof.
extremely unwilling to answer questions. Not friendly with students

Cannot tell you how awful she is. Knows nothing about even basic economics. Answer keys were often wrong/not released before exams - useless for studying. Arrogant and blames her own incompetence on students. Loses homework assignments/forgets to grade but never tells you. I don't know how she is still here. Really deserves a 0 rating.

Could not care less about the students. Inconsistent. Told students not to worry about writing down the ressitation section then threatened to take off points because of it. Grades don't reflect understand. Will not give any grace. If there's a multi part question and you get one part wrong, everything after that will be counted wrong as well.
Hard grading for this most basic econ course! Not responding the emails! Horrible!
full of lies. she wrote that 73-100 is a curved class in the syllabus and no curve was implemented. how bad can she really get?

Carol Goldburg is quite possibly the worst professor you'll ever meet. The tests are only half-relevant to the subject, the course is very poorly run, and she doesn't respond to emails or even show up to her own office hours. The fact that she's still employed is a disgrace to Carnegie Mellon. Prepare for an extremely hard first midterm.
Giving her even 1.0 is being nice. She should not be a professor here, plain out terrible, disorganized, etc. It's funny how she got all four degrees of her's at CMU and yet she is so bad.
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Tough grader', 'So many papers']

rComments: Worst professor ever! The seminar courses should have been an easy A since we don't have tests. But this professor make things incredibly difficult. She is so disorganized during class, may be due to the fact that she doesn't understand materials herself. I feel so unfair to receive a C, given that I showed up everytime and did all the homework
Very harsh grader, docks points for simple math that no one needs to use, except her. Does not know econ, and does not respond to emails. Horrible overall.
Horrible professor. Not willing to help students.
She didn't even know the material. She just shadowed other teachers and tried to BS the material, but she often didn't understand.

Took over for another professor while she had a baby.  No interest in helping students, poor lectures to the point that she did not even know her own lectures.  Tests were made to have less room after they had been extended by previous professor.  Professor caused the class to be more confusing that with the previous professor.

Awesome professor. Very enthusiastic every day. He goes to great lengths to make sure even H&SS kids have understanding of practical physics. I'd highly recommend taking a class with him--particularly Physics for Future Presidents. Very easy and fun.

Teaches Physics for future presidents with another teacher. He's the better of the two and a cool guy. Very interesting class and recommended to those who do not need a real physics class as a requirement. VERY easy B and with some effort, an A is not too hard to get (only need an 85). Besides that, not much work and the class is interesting.
Excellent professor and very friendly
Very intelligent and good Indian professor.  He knows his stuff and can teach very well; I doubt anyone out there knows as much as he does.  No problem with his accent or understanding his class.
Loves to take lectures on humorous side tangents, but they're usually interesting enough.  Hates chewing gum and incorrect pronunciation of words such as "orthogonal".  Very insightful.

I'm sure he's a great dude outside the classroom, but he's difficult to appreciate as a professor of art history. The class was boring, disorganized, and poorly conducted. Read the textbook if you want to learn the material.

Might be the worst professor at NYU. You dont know your grade until the last minute, the criteria is so unclear that you would just end up with an B. Absolutly no one listens to his class - I would rather sit and do nothign at Washington Square Park than do go to one of his lectures.
Terrible professor, terrible lectures. Everybody falls asleep during his classes and his grades are also extremely subjective.
Very intelligent Italian professor.  No problem with accent.  Nice guy.  Very into his research and not as much into clear teaching.
French professor, a little trouble with accent.  He knew his material, but couldn't teach it.  Taught French/European statistics to American students.

She was teaching an experimental strategy course.  Very useful and interesting course where you play strategy games.  Her lecture style was a little boring, but the in class exercises were great and helpful.  No problem with her accent.
Very good Indian marketing professor.  Very clear, no problem with accent.  Great examples of commercials.  Learned alot in his class.
A good professor with a fine knowledge of accounting.  Sometimes he let class discussion get in the way of what he wanted to accomplish, but overall no complaints.  Very little accent.

Great Guy. Has a solid understanding of the subject matter. Teaches really well. Easy on exams and grading. Makes great efforts to explain subject matters as clearly and enjoyable as possible and succeeds in doing so. You will definitely love his course.
Very good, clear and helpful Indian professor.  No probleem with accent.  He made very difficult material easy to understand.
Is really interesting. fun to listen to. very enthusiastic

Horrendous lecture organization. Material taught was at the 5th grade level but averages on tests were still C's since they weren't representative of what was taught in class. I hated this course mainly because of her.

Solid teacher and course (Regression) - very easy material to learn if you do the homework and study. She was very nice and available for extra help (i.e. anonymous note card questions after class, office hours, and exam review sessions). Accent is hard to understand at first, but you get used to it.

Professor had no interest in helping students.  Continued to state that students were really stupid if they "super failed" by having a 0 on a rubric that was completely arbitrary and not shown prior to the first test. The rubric jumped from 5 to 4 to 0 with basically no partial credit.  Strong emphasis on vocab and unclear in requirements for tests

Teaches the material quite well, but often appears to advocate extreme ideas that make the class seem like propaganda. Tests and homework are difficult not for the content, but because it's extremely difficult to tell what exactly she wants written. Grades are based on a rubric placing significant emphasis on economic vocabulary.

He's clearly brilliant, and generally tries to be helpful and approachable, despite his busy schedule. However, he tends to be a bit disorganized and scatterbrained. Subject matter is interesting, especially given his expertise. Definitely one of the smartest profs the dept. has to offer, and seems like a nice person, too.  I would recommend him.
He is helpful if you go to office hours. He can sometimes stumble over words but overall can communicate organic chemistry in a simple way.
Class is not mandatory, but is helpful for learning the material.  No hmwks, so studying is up to you. Pretty boring, but it's hard to make organic chem 2 interesting.
Pay attention in lecture and study decently for quizzes (they can be hard). Pretty interesting guy
Great teacher- funny, passionate, willing to work with you to explain concepts. However, his exams and quizzes are very difficult.
great
Had him for BSE and Bus Law - great prof, I enjoyed going to lecture, he told great stories. There was no homework, but quizzes and exams were hard (big curve though). Overall learned a lot.
Great professor.  Very passionate about law, tells useful/funny stories, huge curve, no homework, just exams and quizzes.
law class - no hw, projects, or exams, huge curve. tells interesting stories
Hardest professor ever but he's awesome. I got a C and I don't regret taking it at all.
Lots of work for a 9-unit class, but I most certainly learned linear algebra.  Topics at the end (eigenstuff --> spectral theorem) were a bit rushed, though.  Take if you're up for the challenge.

Class: Opera Since Wagner. Fallon is very big into teaching students about life skills in research, but he doesn't take the time to truly discuss each opera.  The quizzes are "did you read"-type.  The 10-page paper assignment is fair.  Do not expect any discussion or learning in class. But he does care for students, and is readily available.
Fantastic teacher. Very passionate about what he teaches, is well prepared and very available for office hours, very quick at answering emails.

Took Concepts and Graph Theory from him... If you've already had a normal class in or have some background in whatever Schaeffer is teaching, and want to gain a more formal, rigorous understanding of the material, his class is for you. Otherwise, wait for someone less pedantic.
He is the man. All you do is write one paper and his standards for writing quality are low. Pretty easy if you show up and listen.
Fun class, really easy. About a month of cool stories about math, and a single large paper about like any topic.

I love him, but he's a horrible teacher. Most all students aren't as smart as him, but he doesn't compensate. He likes abstraction too much to help most students. It's possible to get a good grade in his classes with little work if he trusts that you're bright, however that doesn't help learning either. But try to get him off-topic; he's hilarious.
I took this guy 30 years ago, and he could not teach then.  Seems some things never change. I am a college math professor in spite of the fact I got a "D" in his class my senior year.

Good luck. I came to every class, diligently took notes, read the book, tried the HW... and got nowhere. Dropped the class, took Matrix the next semester, and suddenly everything actually made sense. Maybe it's b/c I prefer numbers and closed solutions to random garbled letters, but maybe it's because no one understood what he was trying to teach.
He is the awesomest man alive. And his wife makes great breakfast.
No Comments
